\textbf{Example 2: }What does the binomial theorem tell us about $(a+1)^p\pmod p$? Use this result to complete the proof by induction. $a^p \equiv a\pmod p$
\\
\\
\textbf{Solution: }
Base case: a = 1
$1^p \equiv 1 \pmod p$
The base case is clearly true.
\\
Suppose $p|a^{p-a}$ (i.e., p divides $a^p-a$). Then examine $(a+1)^p-(a+1)$. From the binomial theorem,$(a+1)^p=a^p+{{p}\choose{1}}a^{p-1}+{{p}\choose{2}}a^{p-2}+...+{{p}\choose{p-1}}a+1$ 	
\\
This means:
$(a+1)^p-a^p-1={{p}\choose{1}}a^{p-1}+{{p}\choose{2}}a^{p-2}+...+{{p}\choose{p-1}}a.$	
\\
But p divides the right side, so it also divides the left side. Combining with the induction hypothesis gives that p divides the sum
 $[(a+1)^p-a^p-1]+(a^p-a)=(a+1)^p-(a+1)$
